clear diplomacy more than four decades ago. Beyond highlighting the importance of this period, the book explains how and why British nuclear diplomacy evolved during Wilson's leadership. Cabinet discussions, financial crises, and international tensions encouraged a degree of flexibility in the pursuit of strategic independence and the creation of a non-proliferation treaty. Gill shows us that British nuclear diplomacy was a series of compromises, an intricate blend of political, economic, and strategic considerations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aNuclear weaponsxGovernment policyzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 4aBritain. 4aCold War. 4aDiplomacy. 4aHarold Wilson. 4aNon-Proliferation Treaty. 4aNuclear Weapons. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804788588zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788588.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles